</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Image-guided breast biopsy with stereotactic, ultrasonographic, or magnetic resonance imaging guidance has become an integral component of every breast imaging program. It has many advantages over open surgical biopsy, including lower cost, lower patient morbidity, faster patient recovery, and minimal to no scarring, with equal accuracy to that of open surgical biopsy. Successful completion of a breast biopsy begins with thorough preprocedural planning to choose the appropriate imaging modality and most efficient biopsy approach. Patient mental and physical comorbidities, anticoagulation status, small or thin breasts, and breast implants, as well as lesion conspicuity and posterior, superficial, axillary, or subareolar location, pose technical challenges to successful image-guided breast biopsy that must be overcome. When biopsy is performed with use of a different imaging modality than that used to initially identify the target, careful preprocedural multimodality radiologic correlation, postprocedural identification of the biopsy marker location, and radiologic-pathologic correlation must be undertaken to ensure accurate biopsy of the intended target with use of the different modality. If, after employing all available strategic and procedural modifications, image-guided breast biopsy cannot be performed, then surgical excision of the intended target should be recommended at the time of biopsy cancellation to avoid a delay in diagnosis. This article reviews patient and lesion factors that pose technical challenges to successful breast biopsy and presents strategies and procedural modifications that aid in successful completion of breast biopsy in challenging situations.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160117">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017160117">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig1a.jpeg" height="1436" width="916" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Biopsy needle fired outside a thin breast in a 60-year-old woman. The compression thickness of the breast was 21 mm. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> spot magnification view shows a cluster of punctate and round calcifications (arrow) associated with a round mass in the outer breast. <b>(b, c)</b> At stereotactic-guided biopsy, the <i>−</i>15° <b>(b)</b> and +15° <b>(c)</b> stereotactic pair images show a shortened sampling chamber needle fired outside the breast (arrow), away from the calcifications (circle). The needle was dialed into the calcifications, which were seen on a specimen radiograph (not shown). Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample revealed papilloma with atypical features associated with calcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig1b.jpeg" height="1436" width="1570" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Biopsy needle fired outside a thin breast in a 60-year-old woman. The compression thickness of the breast was 21 mm. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> spot magnification view shows a cluster of punctate and round calcifications (arrow) associated with a round mass in the outer breast. <b>(b, c)</b> At stereotactic-guided biopsy, the <i>−</i>15° <b>(b)</b> and +15° <b>(c)</b> stereotactic pair images show a shortened sampling chamber needle fired outside the breast (arrow), away from the calcifications (circle). The needle was dialed into the calcifications, which were seen on a specimen radiograph (not shown). Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample revealed papilloma with atypical features associated with calcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig1c.jpeg" height="1436" width="1214" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Biopsy needle fired outside a thin breast in a 60-year-old woman. The compression thickness of the breast was 21 mm. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> spot magnification view shows a cluster of punctate and round calcifications (arrow) associated with a round mass in the outer breast. <b>(b, c)</b> At stereotactic-guided biopsy, the <i>−</i>15° <b>(b)</b> and +15° <b>(c)</b> stereotactic pair images show a shortened sampling chamber needle fired outside the breast (arrow), away from the calcifications (circle). The needle was dialed into the calcifications, which were seen on a specimen radiograph (not shown). Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample revealed papilloma with atypical features associated with calcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig2.jpeg" height="1560" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Diagram shows use of a sponge (light blue) against a solid compression plate (on right) to increase breast thickness for MR imaging–guided biopsy in a thin breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig3a.jpeg" height="1909" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Displacement of a retropectoral silicone breast implant for successful stereotactic-guided biopsy in a 45-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left mediolateral oblique (<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr>) image shows a cluster of punctate calcifications (arrow) in the upper outer quadrant. <b>*</b> = retropectoral silicone implant. <b>(b)</b> Left lateral implant-displaced view shows the calcifications (arrow) further from the chest wall. The implant was displaced posteriorly to allow easier and safer access to the calcifications and is outside the field of view. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample showed columnar cell change and apocrine cysts associated with the calcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig3b.jpeg" height="1909" width="1303" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Displacement of a retropectoral silicone breast implant for successful stereotactic-guided biopsy in a 45-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left mediolateral oblique (<abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr>) image shows a cluster of punctate calcifications (arrow) in the upper outer quadrant. <b>*</b> = retropectoral silicone implant. <b>(b)</b> Left lateral implant-displaced view shows the calcifications (arrow) further from the chest wall. The implant was displaced posteriorly to allow easier and safer access to the calcifications and is outside the field of view. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample showed columnar cell change and apocrine cysts associated with the calcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig4a.jpeg" height="788" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Fine-needle aspiration of a palpable mass abutting a breast implant in a 41-year-old woman with a prior prophylactic mastectomy. <b>(a)</b> Right US image at the site of a palpable abnormality shows an oval, circumscribed, hypoechoic mass (black arrows) abutting the implant (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> US image shows fine-needle (arrowhead) aspiration, which was performed because core needle biopsy was not considered safe owing to the location of the mass (black arrows) atop the implant (white arrows). Cytologic analysis showed no malignant cells and scant myofibroblasts consistent with nodular fasciitis. Close clinical follow-up and referral to a breast surgeon were recommended.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig4b.jpeg" height="788" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Fine-needle aspiration of a palpable mass abutting a breast implant in a 41-year-old woman with a prior prophylactic mastectomy. <b>(a)</b> Right US image at the site of a palpable abnormality shows an oval, circumscribed, hypoechoic mass (black arrows) abutting the implant (white arrows). <b>(b)</b> US image shows fine-needle (arrowhead) aspiration, which was performed because core needle biopsy was not considered safe owing to the location of the mass (black arrows) atop the implant (white arrows). Cytologic analysis showed no malignant cells and scant myofibroblasts consistent with nodular fasciitis. Close clinical follow-up and referral to a breast surgeon were recommended.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig5a.jpeg" height="1690" width="992" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Mammographic localization used to identify a small mass in a large fatty breast for US-guided biopsy. The patient was a 53-year-old woman who could not tolerate prone stereotactic biopsy because of claustrophobia. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a small anterior mass (white arrow) with a US correlate (not shown) and a small posterior mass (black arrow) without an initial US correlate. <b>(b)</b> Mammogram shows the alphanumeric grid used for localization of the posterior mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image obtained with use of a BB placed on the overlying skin shows a small hypoechoic mass (arrows) in a fatty background. US-guided biopsy of both masses revealed triple-negative invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Postbiopsy left lateral mammogram shows the biopsy marker (arrow) at the site of the posterior mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig5b.jpeg" height="1594" width="953" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Mammographic localization used to identify a small mass in a large fatty breast for US-guided biopsy. The patient was a 53-year-old woman who could not tolerate prone stereotactic biopsy because of claustrophobia. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a small anterior mass (white arrow) with a US correlate (not shown) and a small posterior mass (black arrow) without an initial US correlate. <b>(b)</b> Mammogram shows the alphanumeric grid used for localization of the posterior mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image obtained with use of a BB placed on the overlying skin shows a small hypoechoic mass (arrows) in a fatty background. US-guided biopsy of both masses revealed triple-negative invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Postbiopsy left lateral mammogram shows the biopsy marker (arrow) at the site of the posterior mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig5c.jpeg" height="1690" width="1657" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Mammographic localization used to identify a small mass in a large fatty breast for US-guided biopsy. The patient was a 53-year-old woman who could not tolerate prone stereotactic biopsy because of claustrophobia. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a small anterior mass (white arrow) with a US correlate (not shown) and a small posterior mass (black arrow) without an initial US correlate. <b>(b)</b> Mammogram shows the alphanumeric grid used for localization of the posterior mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image obtained with use of a BB placed on the overlying skin shows a small hypoechoic mass (arrows) in a fatty background. US-guided biopsy of both masses revealed triple-negative invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Postbiopsy left lateral mammogram shows the biopsy marker (arrow) at the site of the posterior mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig5d.jpeg" height="1594" width="1697" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Mammographic localization used to identify a small mass in a large fatty breast for US-guided biopsy. The patient was a 53-year-old woman who could not tolerate prone stereotactic biopsy because of claustrophobia. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> view shows a small anterior mass (white arrow) with a US correlate (not shown) and a small posterior mass (black arrow) without an initial US correlate. <b>(b)</b> Mammogram shows the alphanumeric grid used for localization of the posterior mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image obtained with use of a BB placed on the overlying skin shows a small hypoechoic mass (arrows) in a fatty background. US-guided biopsy of both masses revealed triple-negative invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Postbiopsy left lateral mammogram shows the biopsy marker (arrow) at the site of the posterior mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig6a.jpeg" height="1561" width="1147" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Use of an adjacent breast landmark to locate a small US correlate for a mammographic mass in a 60-year-old woman with a predominantly fatty breast. <b>(a)</b> Right lateral mammogram shows a small mass (white arrow) in the upper outer quadrant, with dystrophic calcifications (black arrow) seen anterior to the mass. <b>(b)</b> At US, the calcifications produced shadowing at the 9-o’clock position, 7–8 cm from the nipple (not shown), and were used to locate a small hypoechoic mass (white arrows) at the 9-o’clock position, 9–11 cm from the nipple. US-guided biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(c)</b> Lateral mammogram obtained after biopsy shows the biopsy marker (white arrow) at the site of the mass and posterior to the dystrophic calcifications (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig6b.jpeg" height="1561" width="1370" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Use of an adjacent breast landmark to locate a small US correlate for a mammographic mass in a 60-year-old woman with a predominantly fatty breast. <b>(a)</b> Right lateral mammogram shows a small mass (white arrow) in the upper outer quadrant, with dystrophic calcifications (black arrow) seen anterior to the mass. <b>(b)</b> At US, the calcifications produced shadowing at the 9-o’clock position, 7–8 cm from the nipple (not shown), and were used to locate a small hypoechoic mass (white arrows) at the 9-o’clock position, 9–11 cm from the nipple. US-guided biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(c)</b> Lateral mammogram obtained after biopsy shows the biopsy marker (white arrow) at the site of the mass and posterior to the dystrophic calcifications (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig6c.jpeg" height="1561" width="1182" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Use of an adjacent breast landmark to locate a small US correlate for a mammographic mass in a 60-year-old woman with a predominantly fatty breast. <b>(a)</b> Right lateral mammogram shows a small mass (white arrow) in the upper outer quadrant, with dystrophic calcifications (black arrow) seen anterior to the mass. <b>(b)</b> At US, the calcifications produced shadowing at the 9-o’clock position, 7–8 cm from the nipple (not shown), and were used to locate a small hypoechoic mass (white arrows) at the 9-o’clock position, 9–11 cm from the nipple. US-guided biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(c)</b> Lateral mammogram obtained after biopsy shows the biopsy marker (white arrow) at the site of the mass and posterior to the dystrophic calcifications (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig7a.jpeg" height="1590" width="1469" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Use of landmarks to identify a target in a background of moderate parenchymal enhancement in a 50-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing mass (arrow) in the lower inner quadrant. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed epithelial hyperplasia and pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia, which was considered benign and concordant. Short-interval follow-up MR imaging at 6 months (not shown) showed an unchanged enhancing mass with susceptibility artifact from the biopsy marker inferior to the mass, and the initial biopsy was therefore thought to be possibly inaccurate. <b>(b)</b> Left sagittal contrast-enhanced MR image obtained at repeat MR imaging–guided biopsy shows the biopsy clip (black arrow) inferior to the enhancing mass, with central susceptibility artifact (white arrow) from the biopsy obturator. Repeat MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig7b.jpeg" height="1590" width="1181" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Use of landmarks to identify a target in a background of moderate parenchymal enhancement in a 50-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing mass (arrow) in the lower inner quadrant. MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed epithelial hyperplasia and pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia, which was considered benign and concordant. Short-interval follow-up MR imaging at 6 months (not shown) showed an unchanged enhancing mass with susceptibility artifact from the biopsy marker inferior to the mass, and the initial biopsy was therefore thought to be possibly inaccurate. <b>(b)</b> Left sagittal contrast-enhanced MR image obtained at repeat MR imaging–guided biopsy shows the biopsy clip (black arrow) inferior to the enhancing mass, with central susceptibility artifact (white arrow) from the biopsy obturator. Repeat MR imaging–guided biopsy revealed invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig8a.jpeg" height="1219" width="1647" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Photographs of the “arm-through-the-hole” technique for stereotactic-guided biopsy of a posterior target. <b>(a)</b> The patient’s arm is pulled through the hole in the prone stereotactic biopsy table, and the arm is supported on a pillow. <b>(b)</b> The biopsy can be performed by using a lateral or <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> approach, and more-posterior tissue is accessed during the procedure because it can be pulled into the compression plate with the “arm-through-the-hole” technique.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig8b.jpeg" height="1219" width="1302" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Photographs of the “arm-through-the-hole” technique for stereotactic-guided biopsy of a posterior target. <b>(a)</b> The patient’s arm is pulled through the hole in the prone stereotactic biopsy table, and the arm is supported on a pillow. <b>(b)</b> The biopsy can be performed by using a lateral or <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> approach, and more-posterior tissue is accessed during the procedure because it can be pulled into the compression plate with the “arm-through-the-hole” technique.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig9a.jpeg" height="1637" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Use of local anesthesia to elevate a posterior mass off the chest wall during US-guided biopsy, thus allowing safe needle excursion, in a 32-year-old woman with a retropectoral silicone implant. <b>(a)</b> Right <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view shows a palpable, circumscribed, oval mass (arrows) at a posterior depth. <b>*</b> = retropectoral silicone implant. <b>(b)</b> At US-guided biopsy, a needle (white arrow) was used to inject local anesthesia posterior to the oval hypoechoic mass (black arrows), producing an anesthesia cushion or “bubble” (arrowhead) to elevate the mass off the chest wall and away from the implant (<b>*</b>) and pectoralis muscle. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy specimen revealed fibroadenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig9b.jpeg" height="1026" width="1716" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Use of local anesthesia to elevate a posterior mass off the chest wall during US-guided biopsy, thus allowing safe needle excursion, in a 32-year-old woman with a retropectoral silicone implant. <b>(a)</b> Right <abbr title="mediolateral oblique">MLO</abbr> view shows a palpable, circumscribed, oval mass (arrows) at a posterior depth. <b>*</b> = retropectoral silicone implant. <b>(b)</b> At US-guided biopsy, a needle (white arrow) was used to inject local anesthesia posterior to the oval hypoechoic mass (black arrows), producing an anesthesia cushion or “bubble” (arrowhead) to elevate the mass off the chest wall and away from the implant (<b>*</b>) and pectoralis muscle. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy specimen revealed fibroadenoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig10a.jpeg" height="663" width="1659" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Use of local anesthesia to depress superficial masses away from the skin surface during US-guided biopsy. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a palpable, superficial, circumscribed mass (arrows) in the hypodermis. <b>(b)</b> US image obtained during spring-loaded US-guided biopsy shows a needle (arrowhead) being used to inject local anesthesia (black arrow) without epinephrine to depress the superficial mass (white arrows) away from the skin, allowing more space for the biopsy needle. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample revealed hemangioma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig10b.jpeg" height="663" width="1491" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Use of local anesthesia to depress superficial masses away from the skin surface during US-guided biopsy. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a palpable, superficial, circumscribed mass (arrows) in the hypodermis. <b>(b)</b> US image obtained during spring-loaded US-guided biopsy shows a needle (arrowhead) being used to inject local anesthesia (black arrow) without epinephrine to depress the superficial mass (white arrows) away from the skin, allowing more space for the biopsy needle. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample revealed hemangioma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig11a.jpeg" height="1400" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Use of a “no-throw” biopsy device for safe US-guided biopsy in the axilla of a 65-year-old woman with ipsilateral mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> US image from the left axilla shows a rounded lymph node (arrows) with a thickened cortex and effaced hilum. <b>(b, c)</b> US images obtained during US-guided biopsy with a “no-throw” needle shows the sampling chamber (black arrows) within the abnormal lymph node open in <b>b</b> and closed in <b>c</b>, while the needle tip (white arrow) did not move in the axillary soft tissues. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample showed metastatic carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig11b.jpeg" height="804" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Use of a “no-throw” biopsy device for safe US-guided biopsy in the axilla of a 65-year-old woman with ipsilateral mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> US image from the left axilla shows a rounded lymph node (arrows) with a thickened cortex and effaced hilum. <b>(b, c)</b> US images obtained during US-guided biopsy with a “no-throw” needle shows the sampling chamber (black arrows) within the abnormal lymph node open in <b>b</b> and closed in <b>c</b>, while the needle tip (white arrow) did not move in the axillary soft tissues. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample showed metastatic carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig11c.jpeg" height="926" width="1450" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Use of a “no-throw” biopsy device for safe US-guided biopsy in the axilla of a 65-year-old woman with ipsilateral mixed invasive ductal and lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> US image from the left axilla shows a rounded lymph node (arrows) with a thickened cortex and effaced hilum. <b>(b, c)</b> US images obtained during US-guided biopsy with a “no-throw” needle shows the sampling chamber (black arrows) within the abnormal lymph node open in <b>b</b> and closed in <b>c</b>, while the needle tip (white arrow) did not move in the axillary soft tissues. Pathologic analysis of the biopsy sample showed metastatic carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig12a.jpeg" height="1610" width="1118" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. US-guided biopsy of subareolar calcifications in a 61-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Right lateral magnification mammogram shows subareolar linear branching calcifications (arrows). Because of thin breast tissue at the location of the calcifications, stereotactic-guided biopsy was not performed. <b>(b)</b> US image shows linear calcifications (arrows) in a duct without an associated mass. A BB was placed on the skin overlying the calcifications. <b>(c)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> magnification tangential mammogram shows the BB (circled) on the skin that correlates the calcifications found at US with the mammographic calcifications (arrows). US-guided biopsy revealed ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig12b.jpeg" height="810" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. US-guided biopsy of subareolar calcifications in a 61-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Right lateral magnification mammogram shows subareolar linear branching calcifications (arrows). Because of thin breast tissue at the location of the calcifications, stereotactic-guided biopsy was not performed. <b>(b)</b> US image shows linear calcifications (arrows) in a duct without an associated mass. A BB was placed on the skin overlying the calcifications. <b>(c)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> magnification tangential mammogram shows the BB (circled) on the skin that correlates the calcifications found at US with the mammographic calcifications (arrows). US-guided biopsy revealed ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig12c.jpeg" height="1610" width="1331" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. US-guided biopsy of subareolar calcifications in a 61-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Right lateral magnification mammogram shows subareolar linear branching calcifications (arrows). Because of thin breast tissue at the location of the calcifications, stereotactic-guided biopsy was not performed. <b>(b)</b> US image shows linear calcifications (arrows) in a duct without an associated mass. A BB was placed on the skin overlying the calcifications. <b>(c)</b> Right <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> magnification tangential mammogram shows the BB (circled) on the skin that correlates the calcifications found at US with the mammographic calcifications (arrows). US-guided biopsy revealed ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig13a.jpeg" height="1896" width="1060" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Necessity of mammographic-US correlation to ensure that the initial target was biopsied with use of a different modality in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram shows a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the upper outer quadrant. The presumed US correlate (not shown) underwent fine-needle aspiration, which revealed a bloody aspirate and nondiagnostic cytologic findings. <b>(b)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram obtained after aspiration shows the biopsy marker (black arrow) anterior to and not corresponding to the developing asymmetry (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram obtained after same-day stereotactic-guided biopsy shows the <i>T</i>-shaped biopsy marker (white arrow) in the developing asymmetry. Pathologic analysis revealed adenosis, papillomatosis, and columnar cell hyperplasia. Black arrow = fine-needle aspiration biopsy marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig13b.jpeg" height="1896" width="1322" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Necessity of mammographic-US correlation to ensure that the initial target was biopsied with use of a different modality in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram shows a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the upper outer quadrant. The presumed US correlate (not shown) underwent fine-needle aspiration, which revealed a bloody aspirate and nondiagnostic cytologic findings. <b>(b)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram obtained after aspiration shows the biopsy marker (black arrow) anterior to and not corresponding to the developing asymmetry (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram obtained after same-day stereotactic-guided biopsy shows the <i>T</i>-shaped biopsy marker (white arrow) in the developing asymmetry. Pathologic analysis revealed adenosis, papillomatosis, and columnar cell hyperplasia. Black arrow = fine-needle aspiration biopsy marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig13c.jpeg" height="1896" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Necessity of mammographic-US correlation to ensure that the initial target was biopsied with use of a different modality in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram shows a developing asymmetry (arrow) in the upper outer quadrant. The presumed US correlate (not shown) underwent fine-needle aspiration, which revealed a bloody aspirate and nondiagnostic cytologic findings. <b>(b)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram obtained after aspiration shows the biopsy marker (black arrow) anterior to and not corresponding to the developing asymmetry (white arrow). <b>(c)</b> Left <abbr title="craniocaudal">CC</abbr> mammogram obtained after same-day stereotactic-guided biopsy shows the <i>T</i>-shaped biopsy marker (white arrow) in the developing asymmetry. Pathologic analysis revealed adenosis, papillomatosis, and columnar cell hyperplasia. Black arrow = fine-needle aspiration biopsy marker.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig14a.jpeg" height="1525" width="1270" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Necessity of multimodality correlation after US-guided biopsy of a mass seen at MR imaging in a 52-year-old woman recently diagnosed with contralateral invasive lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows medial (arrow) and lateral (circle) masses in the upper breast. <b>(b)</b> Right CC spot view obtained after US-guided biopsy of the presumed US correlates shows both biopsy markers (arrows) lateral to the nipple. An irregular mass (circle) medial to the nipple corresponds to the enhancing mass seen at MR imaging. Same-day stereotactic-guided biopsy of the medial mass revealed invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig14b.jpeg" height="1525" width="1680" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Necessity of multimodality correlation after US-guided biopsy of a mass seen at MR imaging in a 52-year-old woman recently diagnosed with contralateral invasive lobular carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows medial (arrow) and lateral (circle) masses in the upper breast. <b>(b)</b> Right CC spot view obtained after US-guided biopsy of the presumed US correlates shows both biopsy markers (arrows) lateral to the nipple. An irregular mass (circle) medial to the nipple corresponds to the enhancing mass seen at MR imaging. Same-day stereotactic-guided biopsy of the medial mass revealed invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig15a.jpeg" height="1275" width="1487" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Postbiopsy MR imaging used to confirm that the intended MR imaging–detected lesion was correctly biopsied with US guidance. The patient was a 41-year-old woman who underwent ipsilateral breast conservation therapy 8 months earlier for invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing oval mass (arrow) in the lower outer quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Right axial nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained after US-guided biopsy shows susceptibility artifact (arrow) from the biopsy marker in the oval mass. Pathologic analysis revealed nodular dense stroma with pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig15b.jpeg" height="1275" width="1663" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Postbiopsy MR imaging used to confirm that the intended MR imaging–detected lesion was correctly biopsied with US guidance. The patient was a 41-year-old woman who underwent ipsilateral breast conservation therapy 8 months earlier for invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows an enhancing oval mass (arrow) in the lower outer quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Right axial nonenhanced T1-weighted MR image obtained after US-guided biopsy shows susceptibility artifact (arrow) from the biopsy marker in the oval mass. Pathologic analysis revealed nodular dense stroma with pseudoangiomatous stromal hyperplasia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig16a.jpeg" height="1515" width="1299" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Cancelled MR imaging–guided biopsy requiring short-interval follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Right axial short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) MR image shows a cyst (arrow) in the lower outer quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows a focal nonmass enhancement (arrow) adjacent to the cyst seen in <b>a</b>. MR imaging–guided biopsy was cancelled when no nonmass enhancement was identified at the time of biopsy. Short-interval follow-up MR imaging performed 4 months later (not shown) showed persistent nonmass enhancement. <b>(c)</b> US image obtained during US-guided biopsy shows the cyst (white arrow), which was used as a landmark to identify an adjacent subtle hyperechoic area (black arrow) corresponding to the nonmass enhancement seen at MR imaging. Pathologic analysis revealed ductal carcinoma in situ. Arrowhead = biopsy needle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig16b.jpeg" height="1515" width="1351" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Cancelled MR imaging–guided biopsy requiring short-interval follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Right axial short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) MR image shows a cyst (arrow) in the lower outer quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows a focal nonmass enhancement (arrow) adjacent to the cyst seen in <b>a</b>. MR imaging–guided biopsy was cancelled when no nonmass enhancement was identified at the time of biopsy. Short-interval follow-up MR imaging performed 4 months later (not shown) showed persistent nonmass enhancement. <b>(c)</b> US image obtained during US-guided biopsy shows the cyst (white arrow), which was used as a landmark to identify an adjacent subtle hyperechoic area (black arrow) corresponding to the nonmass enhancement seen at MR imaging. Pathologic analysis revealed ductal carcinoma in situ. Arrowhead = biopsy needle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017160117/asset/images/large/rg.2017160117.fig16c.jpeg" height="796" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Cancelled MR imaging–guided biopsy requiring short-interval follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Right axial short τ inversion-recovery (STIR) MR image shows a cyst (arrow) in the lower outer quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Right axial contrast-enhanced MR image shows a focal nonmass enhancement (arrow) adjacent to the cyst seen in <b>a</b>. MR imaging–guided biopsy was cancelled when no nonmass enhancement was identified at the time of biopsy. Short-interval follow-up MR imaging performed 4 months later (not shown) showed persistent nonmass enhancement. <b>(c)</b> US image obtained during US-guided biopsy shows the cyst (white arrow), which was used as a landmark to identify an adjacent subtle hyperechoic area (black arrow) corresponding to the nonmass enhancement seen at MR imaging. Pathologic analysis revealed ductal carcinoma in situ. Arrowhead = biopsy needle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017160117&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Parker SH, Burbank F, Jackman RJ, et al. Percutaneous large-core breast biopsy: a multi-institutional study. <em>Radiology</em> 1994;193(2):359–364.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiology.193.2.7972743">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7972743/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Percutaneous+large-core+breast+biopsy%3A+a+multi-institutional+study&amp;author=SH+Parker&amp;author=F+Burbank&amp;author=RJ+Jackman&amp;publication_year=1994&amp;journal=Radiology&amp;pages=359-364&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiology.193.2.7972743&amp;pmid=7972743">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Meyer JE, Smith DN, Lester SC, et al. Large-core needle biopsy of nonpalpable breast lesions. <em>JAMA</em> 1999;281(17): 1638–1641.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.281.17.1638">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10235159/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Large-core+needle+biopsy